body:
Consider the following circuit:

``` mlir
firrtl.circuit "Foo" {
  firrtl.layer @A  bind {}
  firrtl.module @Foo(out %out: !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>) {
    // Wire cannot be sunk because it has a connect to a port.
    %wire = firrtl.wire : !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>
    firrtl.connect %out, %wire : !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>

    // A subfield of wire can be sunk.  This then trips the layerblock verifier
    // because this "captures a non-passive type".
    %wire_a = firrtl.subfield %wire[a] : !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>
    firrtl.layerblock @A {
      %0 = firrtl.node %wire_a : !firrtl.uint<1>
    }
  }
}
```

When running this through FIRRTL's layer sink pass (which tries to sink operations into layer blocks when possible, currently using only dominance info):

```
# circt-opt chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir -pass-pipeline='builtin.module(firrtl.circuit(firrtl.module(firrtl-layer-sink)))' -debug-only=firrtl-layer-sink -mlir-print-ir-after-all
===- Running LayerSink ------------------------------------------------------===
Module: 'Foo'
chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir:7:5: error: 'firrtl.layerblock' op captures an operand which is not a passive type
    firrtl.layerblock @A {
    ^
chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir:7:5: note: see current operation: 
"firrtl.layerblock"() ({
  %1 = "firrtl.subfield"(%0) {fieldIndex = 0 : i32} : (!firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
  %2 = "firrtl.node"(%1) {annotations = [], name = "", nameKind = #firrtl<name_kind droppable_name>} : (!firrtl.uint<1>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
}) {layerName = @A} : () -> ()
chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir:5:13: note: operand is defined here
    %wire = firrtl.wire : !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>
            ^
chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir:6:15: note: operand is used here
    %wire_a = firrtl.subfield %wire[a] : !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>
```

The final MLIR is shown below:

``` mlir
"firrtl.module"() ({
^bb0(%arg0: !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>):
  %0 = "firrtl.wire"() {annotations = [], name = "wire", nameKind = #firrtl<name_kind droppable_name>} : () -> !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>
  "firrtl.layerblock"() ({
    %1 = "firrtl.subfield"(%0) {fieldIndex = 0 : i32} : (!firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
    %2 = "firrtl.node"(%1) {annotations = [], name = "", nameKind = #firrtl<name_kind droppable_name>} : (!firrtl.uint<1>) -> !firrtl.uint<1>
  }) {layerName = @A} : () -> ()
  "firrtl.connect"(%arg0, %0) : (!firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>, !firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>) -> ()
}) {annotations = [], convention = #firrtl<convention internal>, layers = [], parameters = [], portAnnotations = [], portDirections = array<i1: true>, portLocations = [loc("chisel-non-passive-capture.mlir":4:26)], portNames = ["out"], portSyms = [], portTypes = [!firrtl.bundle<a: uint<1>, b flip: uint<1>>], sym_name = "Foo"} : () -> ()
```

I think that this is actually fine and is a bug in the verifier. While the subfield is capturing a non-passive type, it's result type is passive. There is no way that a user could drive through that subfield based on FIRRTL connection semantics. The right verifier check here is probably to check the result type and not the capture in this case.

#### Context

This showed up for an integration test in upstream Chisel when automatically putting certain operations into layer blocks. Memories can have aggregates that are preserved later in the pipeline than `LowerTypes` and this can create the situation above. See: https://github.com/chipsalliance/chisel/actions/runs/10275646368/job/28434663302?pr=4323#step:8:85
